text:
come, sit with me

staring into the dark, unseeing the forlorn, lonely room, 
a scared teenager sat,
upright, 
holding her swollen belly. 
never does this vigil, 
of chilled winter keeping tempo on window panes, 
never does it relinquish itself. 
a frozen sentinel observing the shift of light on the horizon, 
fetal against unfinished floorboards, grasped photo in hand.

facebook cannot tell you of the ache  resting in the heart of this mountain; 
will not notify or remind of unknown events kept locked inside... mine? 
mined? 
minded? 
buzzfeed cannot tantalize you with headlines of early #metoo whispers
â€”when small town news created narratives of positive politeness;
hurry, 
hush the tones, 
smoothing transgressions lest their peace be destroyed. 
images not made for instagram,
fragments;
fractals;
pieces of light and darkness â€”cannot be edited
â€”cannot be deleted
â€”cannot be shared
memory slide shows, 
hidden film takes,
someone [of authority?]
should have confiscated, locked away... should have.
would have.
could have.

how these years of building faces â€”and fences,
have been cries of injustice for mistakes of men born out upon my flesh... my flesh,
and yours.
how these years have been futile journeys, 
one pilgrimage after the next, 
for the face that once was; for the fence not born of fear.

hear my voice as it quavers, 
brave, bright, true; 
still unforgivingly present.
a voice forged in the fire of our creation,
of countless, cracked imperfections;
also, 
immovable strength. 
come, 
sit with me
this is my heart song, 
sung forward,
bled out.

lived out loud,
â€”in ruby hued rivers, 
deepened pools of crimson anguish,
lit by cotton-candy laughter splashes. 
lived out of bounds,
â€”in chaotic crashing adventures,
punctuated with relationships of pain and passion, 
brought to balance with measured mountain breaths. 
come, sit with me,
hear the story of our birth. 
for someday when you wake,
dear daughter,
you too will not only move mountains:
you are the mountain. 
m.blaschka Â©ï¸ 2018

â€œsubstantialâ€ means the effect of the disability is not minor or trivial, rather significantly affects a personâ€™s ability to carry out routine daily tasks such as getting dressed.
â€œlong-termâ€ means the effects of the condition affect (or are likely to affect) the person for 12 months or more. there are some conditions (such as cancer, multiple schlorisis, hiv), however, where the person is identified as having a disability from the moment of diagnosis.

text:
when i go home i tell my mother
that the men outside were starving
she tells me i must
not dress with my
breasts hanging
said the boys will get hungry
if they see fruit
she tells me to sit with my legs closed
like a woman oughtta
or the men will get angry and fight
said i can avoid all of this trouble
if i just learn to act like a lady
but the problem is
that doesn't even make sense
i can't wrap my head around the fact that
i have to convince half the worlds population
that my body is not their bed [...] because slut shaming is rape culture
virgin praising is rape culture

text:
its not your fault! for anyone who has ever suffered any type of abuse or assault please know that it is not your fault! often people are quick to blame the victim (even yourself) because it's an easier way to process how such acts can be carried out by another person. 
as a child i grew up in an abusive household, my mum watched it happen and did nothing to stop it.  i was hit, never called by my name, had my clothes pulled off me around others then laughed at, and sexually assaulted from the age of 6. it was not my fault and it has taken me years to realise that, i always thought i must have been doing something wrong that made him do that to me, but no it wasn't. it was his fault and his fault alone. the same goes for any victim. i can not stress that enough. 
you are never asking for it, you never deserve it, you are never the reason why. â¤

text: itâ€™s time: itâ€™s time to dispense with buzzwords and canned responses to a national issue we all need to come together to address as citizens of this nation. itâ€™s time to vote and to self-educate in doing so. your tax dollars support your use of the local library. your citizenship entitles you to visit legal libraries. do this. go to the library and learn about the rights â€œtheyâ€ donâ€™t want you to understand. remember that there is a legal defense fund to protect you and support you. this time i am proud to say i utilized my brain instead of giving permission to be shamed for my intellect. itâ€™s time to expect employers to value insight from every single employee in every single industry and nurture a willingness to learn. itâ€™s time to speak up about illness and to stop giving our consent through silence to be stigmatized and discriminated against in the workplace and in life. itâ€™s time to stop firing people because their intelligence, identity, capacity, and disabilities are perceived as a threat to those who have falsely told you they wish to empower you. itâ€™s time to remember that â€œhuman resourcesâ€ is not a resource for humans, but a legal middle â€œmanâ€ solely advocating for the profit of a business. if you are passionate about your work or any thing whatsoever, you must advocate for yourself because those above you in nearly all hierarchies â€” and all genders. *will* try to erase you. theyâ€™ll even ask you to sign your name to consent to your own erasure and in my case they will literally throw you out in the snow if you do not comply. do not comply. choose to have a nosebleed in the snow across the street from a shady alley all alone with all your belongings. choose to walk away even if you feel unsafe in doing so, because nothing is more dangerous or threatening than a workplace who wants to hurt you. yesterday i made eye contact with the executive team of women and men who tried to deny my rights as i stood shivering in the cold. these same folks use the motto â€œwork life balanceâ€. know your rights and tell them you know. itâ€™s time, folks. #selfadvocate #knowyourrights bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
social media seâœ–uality censorship news coming atcha!
.
there's been some shifts happening behind the scenes in response to new laws passed in the us.  platforms like instagram and facebook are cracking down on seâœ– talk (i don't think i'm even free to write that word anymore in case a random bot scans my page and decides to shut it down).
.
and while these new laws i believe have a good intention to protect users from seâœ–ual harassment or unwanted propostions in the era of #metoo, it seems they don't decern well between unsolicited dğŸ¥’ck pics vs. empowering content being offered by healers, coaches, educators, er0tic artists, feminists and therapists.
.
i've heard many of my dear colleagues, peers & mentors have had their pages shut down. all of their educational content and communities lost.
.
right now it's not safe for us to express ourselves on these platforms.
.
it's fucking bullshit and feels like we're moving backwards not forwards.
.
it saddens me and pisses me off, but i'm also not going to waste too much of my energy resisting what is for now.
.
instead i will be playing by the rules on this platform. making everything a bit more pg than it was. sticking to things like "pleasure" and "sensuality" (i wasn't super explict to being with... something in my intuition and body has always warned me to tread lightly on social media because we don't have much control over it).
.
but not all hope is lost. my work encompasses so much more than just womens seâœ–ual empowerment.
.
it's about women connecting to their truth and inner guidance. owning all of who they are. creating deep safety in their bones. and creating a life that feels fucking fabulous.
.
self-love, empowerment and healing is at the core of it all.
.
and that journey requires that we look at where we've lost parts of ourselves or hold onto shame and fear that needs to be released, which is why it's been so important for us to look at where we have disconnected from our seâœ–uality.
.

.

.

.

.

.

.

â£
â€œafter this confirmation process the public now speaks of â€˜corroborationâ€™ as if it were a requirement when it is not. the effect of this change of narrative is that future sexual assault victims will be even less likely to speak up. why bother when there may not be â€˜corroborating evidenceâ€™ and they have been taught that no one will believe them. as a former sexual assault prosecutor this frightens me. as the father of my 12 year old daughter i am terrified that she will grow up in a world which discusses sexual assault in this manner.â£
â£
therefore, i plan to run for the position of judge of common pleas court where i can assure that all victims of sexual assault have the right to be heard and to seek justice.â€

text:
many college students live off campus and many college student rapes happen off campus. thankfully title ix is there to protect college students who are victims of sexual violence regardless of where it happens. unfortunately that all might change. with the proposed changes colleges will be able to say, not on campus, not our problem. as christendom rape victims, we know how devastating that is. if it happened in a park, or a dark road somewhere, or a friend's house in town they can say it didn't happen here. that doesn't happen here. but it happened. and it's continuing to happen. colleges need to hold their students responsible for the crimes they commit off campus. college need to support their students who are victims of crimes off campus. colleges need to do better, not worse.

text:
#masswomenitâ€™s not every day that you get to hang out with 12,000 passionate, inspired and dedicated women nor is it every day that you hear from nearly 150 leaders, activists, and changemakers who are paving the way for gender equality, protections for women and increased diversity at the top professional levels. the one for women team had just this opportunity last week while attending the massachusetts conference for women.

while we were also there sharing our message that one small gesture can have one big impact and helping our fellow lady bosses finish their holiday shopping (or starting it for some!), it was our immense pleasure to be among the thousands of attendees who heard from the likes of aly raisman, cecile richards, elizabeth gilbert and amal clooney. through personal stories and powerful anecdotes, these powerful women delved into the most pressing matters for women today â€“ from #metoo to chasing your dreams to the ultimate fight for equality.

below weâ€™re sharing some of our favorite takeaways from these inspirational women in the hopes that they inspire you (as they did us!) to stand up, speak out and fight back in the name of women everywhere.

read today's blog post on my takeaways from the massachusetts conference for women!

text:
respect - "time magazine reveals murdered or oppressed journalists as person of the year.
time magazine has named journalists, including a slain saudi arabian writer and a pair of reuters journalists imprisoned by myanmar's government, as its person of the year for 2018, in a cover story headlined "the guardians and the war on truth".
key points:
last year's winners were "the silence breakers" of the #metoo movement
time magazine has named the person of the year since 1927
finalists for this year included a mix of politicians, activists â€” and one royal
the "guardians" are saudi journalist jamal khashoggi; the capital gazette in annapolis, maryland, where five people were shot and killed at the newspaper's offices in june; philippine journalist maria ressa, who has been arrested; and two reuters journalists detained in myanmar for nearly a year, wa lone and kyaw soe oo.
the group of journalists will feature on four covers of the magazine's january issue.
in an essay for the magazine, editor-in-chief edward felsenthal said time selected the journalists "for taking great risks in pursuit of greater truths, for the imperfect but essential quest for facts that are central to civil discourse, for speaking up and speaking out".
mr felsenthal added: "like all human gifts, courage comes to us at varying levels and at varying moments.
"this year we are recognising four journalists and one news organisation who have paid a terrible price to seize the challenge of this moment.
"[the journalists] are representative of a broader fight by countless others around the world â€” as of december 10, at least 52 journalists have been murdered in 2018 â€” who risk all to tell the story of our time."
the person of the year winner is the person or group of people who embody the passing year â€” for better or worse." ~ abc

text:
review â€“ bad feminist, roxane gay
â€¢
itâ€™s amazing what the pressure of a library due date will do! i flew through this in three days and really enjoyed it.
â€¢
in bad feminist, roxane gayâ€™s essays range across a number of topicsâ€”popular culture, weight, reproductive rights, sexual assault, and moreâ€”all viewed through the lenses of feminism and race. she engages the reader directly (â€œgirl...â€) and you feel like youâ€™re hearing from someone you know. many times i found she had a way of putting into words things that had bothered me that iâ€™d been unable to articulate.
â€¢
bad feminism was published in 2014 and yet, in many ways, it seems prescient. with topics such as the ones above, a lot can happen in four years! she writes about rape and sexual assault before #metoo and #timesup. she references louis c.k. before allegations were made against him, sheryl sandberg before facebookâ€™s influence on the 2016 us election, twitter before the proliferation of bots, and even donald trump before, well, everything.
â€¢
and yet (as gay would say). although as a reader you canâ€™t help making connections to more recent events, gayâ€™s perspectives continue to be relevant. sheâ€™s also remarkably self-aware recognizing that her thoughts on an issue are connected with who she is and where sheâ€™s at. she acknowledges where she has privilege and where she doesnâ€™t as well as discussing how her perspectives change with time and age. throughout, gay is inherently human and distinctly herself and i will certainly be reading more of her work in the future.
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

text:
#barbietoo  before i left the house i made sure to dress in something loose that would not be too distracting. as i walk the streets of new york at night,one hand holds my groceries tightly, the other holds my pocket knife. i walk with urgency, my hoodie is up and my headphones in and,which are not playing music, act like a barrier between the men who catcalls and whistles at me. i see a masculine shadow at the end of the street, but i cannot see its owner. i fear itâ€™s a man awaiting my passing. i make a detour and walk across the street. 
as i usually do on a weekend night, i was clubbing and hanging out with my girls. i normally go to gay clubs, but this weekend i went to a straight club.  once i felt a strong grip on my ass, i turned around to say what the hell, but this 6 foot tall frat guy in a polo would not look at me. this is the first time i  had my ass grabbed unsolicitedly. they have the balls to grab me, but they donâ€™t own up to their actions. every 5 minutes i would take a headcount of my girls because the cocky boys would not listen to us when we said we did not want to grind with them. this was the first night where i saw that the boys were not listening to no. it made me wonder why they felt because it was dark and the music was loud that they could do what they want. i was not being listened to. â€œthere is no greater threat to women than men? weâ€™re the number one threat!â€ said louis c.k. in his hbo special. when are men taught to acknowledge boundaries? i should be able to leave and feel safe wherever i go without having to worry. i am tired with the way that men are treating me and other women. every women has there own story with harassment, but to tell mine i am using barbie as my proxy. when i was younger i looked up to her and she was a beacon of indepence and i vividly remember watching rapunzel barbie in my bubblegum pink room thinking â€œlook at all that she can do for herselfâ€. #photo #photography #art #camera #canon #fujifilm #fujitx1 #digital #digitalphoto #digitalphotography #digitalphotos #mirrorless #metoo #barbie #pink #hair #violent #ken #sexualassult

text:
2018 was and will always be a crazy year to remember: 
i had heightened my relationship by moving in together and lost it all in a matter of a couple of months. i had changed my life by stepping up in my career only to have the same person i learned to trust stab me in the back, leaving me sexually assaulted/abused and all by myself in unknown territory. i also tried killing myself, in order to not feel any kind of suffering and to stop my own self from future suffering. but you want to know what kept myself going? strength. the fact that i told myself i needed to do this for me is what kept me going. the battle of depression is something taken more seriously than those who joke over it. life had me vulnerable and those same toxic people i had let into my life will always be toxic. i just hope they have the mindset to change themselves and find inner peace. rather than breaking down someone else's walls only for self pleasures. so here's to 2019. and may i always carry the same weight of strengh i've gained within this year. i'm setting new positive goals for me and i hope nothing and noone will break me down in the process. #selflove #2018recap #metoo #innerstrength #depressionsux

text:
ã€Œ"you got a good strong pair of legs, rose. you should get up and use them."ã€
â€¢
i can't even begin to describe how much this quote means to me. towards the end of my last abusive relationship, i started watching fma:bh. - when edward mentions, 'who needs alchemy when i have them?' it made me realize the family i have around me now, and the scene entirely threw me into tears as i had finally come to notice just how much pain i had overcome and turned into something good.
â€¢
 i've dealt with a lot of inner-problems and demons i am still trying to fight, but i have come out on top. my demons right now are battling with anger, immaturity, and finding out where i belong. anger is my strongest, because i was never allowed to be angry growing up. i had to shut up, sit down, be submissive, and 'let things go'. exes who were abusive were allowed to be closed books, but anything i went through they had to know or else they'd threaten me.
â€¢
i have spent the past year throwing out old toxic people, blocking, ignoring - moving new people into my life who i believe felt my aura and could match what positive role models i needed. i've even thrown out blood relatives who did nothing but cause me anxiety and pain making a mockery of my dogs death.
my mental health is looking so much better due to these new friends in my life, and the new guy in my life. i know what to stand up for now, when compromises are reasonable, and what level of effort should be given without tearing myself apart.
i beat out being suicidal, i beat out severe anxiety and depression, i am beating out immaturity, and i will soon be free of the last few bits of my life that i have no control over, and ready to start my new journey.
â€¢
i have my links here if anyone would like to help out: it means the world to me to have this community â¤ï¸

text:
app-elles is a free safety app for all women and girls who are victims of violence. it meets the main support needs for women faced with violence. it offers, in a simple and intuitive interface, three features : warning, calling and searching for help.

app-elles enables users to quickly alert and easily call friends, family, emergency services, ngos and any revelant contacts. its additional bracelet is connected to an innovative streaming protocol: live and recorded audio streaming, instant replay feature and gps tracking in real time. 
all together, we can fight against violence by using solidarity, mutual help and reciprocal vigilance. to join, download app-elles for free, use it and share it around.ğŸ’œğŸ’œğŸ’œ #app_elles #resonantes #againstviolenceagainstwomen #metoo #wearetryingtochangetheworld #wat2ctw

text: today has consisted of numerous cups of green, white, and black teas in my cup.  we all know life is the effort you put into making it happy. each morning you have to decide to be happy and some days it is a struggle. whenever, you heal from trauma, illness, life events, it is always advised to keep a journal, a special place to keep your thoughts, dreams, setbacks, and milestones of achievement. i have been keeping a journal for sometime, but i recently started sharing this with you, the reader.  yesterday, was a milestone for me and my healing from the numerous traumas and abuses i have experienced in this life.  i have been encouraged to organize my journals for a book that others can read to help them heal. i also have been asked to start a support group locally for those who are victims of domestic abuse, rape, and sexual assault. i have no idea where this journey will take me, but i am going to follow me heart for the answer. #cupoftea #cupofjoy #cupofteareflection #goodlife #healing #synchronicity #listeningtotheuniverse #fabulousafter40 #countingmyblessings #changetheworld #randomactsofkindness #steepedtea #laughter #happy #earlgreytea #mountains #metoo #nomore #rabbithole #love #compassion #strength #light #letitallgo #survivor #fighter #hope #journal #live #journey

text:
as a survivor of childhood sexual abuse, there is no end to the reverberations of my trauma. social media and the news cycle are constant triggers, but just living my daily life can be hard, too.
.
typical conversations can become power struggles if iâ€™m not careful. because i felt so out of control when i was little, i overcompensate for being *in control* now that iâ€™m grown. my default is defensiveness, even when that impenetrable armor is no longer necessary.
.
i know how much anguish stems from being molested or raped as a child. so i need you to know that what happened to you was wrong. and it canâ€™t be repressed. it must come to the surface. .
if youâ€™re ready to fave, identify, and name your sexual trauma, now is your time.
.
beautiful scars is a storytelling agency focused on trauma healing and resiliency. @weresurthrivors is an online platform for black christian women who are also survivors of childhood sexual abuse and/or male sexual violence. by helping survivors face and name their trauma, we create holistic care plans so they can integrate their sexual violation(s) into their faith journeys. ultimately, we shift survivors from silence to storytelling, so they evolve into anti-sexual abuse advocates within their faith communities.
.

.
.

text:
- iâ€™ve stayed pretty quiet about things pertaining to my lawsuit. a lot has gone on that no one knows about that has caused pain, anxiety and bouts of depression. but after this i cannot stay silent any longer. -  @wwd interviewed bruce weber. when asked about me, he had this to say, â€œi hope sometime soon that we have other things to talk aboutâ€. i feel like this statement represents all of fashion in this #metoo moment. they hope that one day this will all blow over. if they ignore it and treat it as a fly in the ointment, they will come away unscathed. if any model wanted to know what the powers that be thinks about them, look no further than that statement. -

i am not a human being. i am a problem, a nuisance, an inconvenience. how dare i stand up for myself and countless other young men that have been sexually abused in the name of â€œartistic expressionâ€. in another interview done by wwd, hercules mag co-owner david vivirido, when asked about sexual assault accusations said, â€œof course itâ€™s not the same as someone accused of something like rapeâ€..... let that sink in real deep. so as long as you donâ€™t rape anybody, you have a place in fashion. this is precedent being set by people in power in such a close knit industry. controlled by a powerful few. -

so my question is, how many young men and women need to come forward for a change to happen? how many lives that have been broken due to the abuse suffered at the hands of photographers, casting directors, and agents will it take for something to be done?? -

i also hope that at some point we will have something else to talk about. because iâ€™m sick and tired of talking about men with power and influence, preying on the vulnerable. iâ€™m sick and tired of talking about people in a position to do something about it, standing by and doing nothing. 
truth is inevitable, and change is coming. -

text:
graduation. the biggest accomplishment of my life. the day i have stopped at nothing to reach. â£
â£
within days of beginning college i fractured my spine and suffered a severe concussion. i was told i may not ever gain back my short-term memory and that i should have been paralyzed. â£
â£
i was raped on the campus of my dream school that i worked so hard to get into. they treated me like i was the criminal and i could no longer tolerate being there. i left behind my 4-year nrotc $200,000 scholarship. one of my superiors told me that if i left that i would never graduate from college, and would find myself pregnant with a minimum wage job soon enough. â£
â£
i overdosed on a bottle of pain medication, but somehow woke up and suffered no long-term damage. â£
â£
i enlisted in the navy, still determined to serve my country. i was diagnosed with ptsd and sent home. â£
â£
i spent almost two years in intensive therapy for being raped not only in my first semester of college, but continuously for a good portion of my childhood. â£
â£
i was hospitalized for four days for a brain aneurism, but returned to school after a short recovery. â£
â£
panic attacks. xanax. tears. hopelessness. fear. loss. debt. self-doubt.â£
â£
i never gave up and was determined to make it to graduation. so i did.â£
â£
#metoo #nevergiveup #highhopesforaliving #womenempowerment #graduation #fighter #determination #womenintech #idefineme #successfulwomen #mystory #iwin #herecomesthechange

tuve la suerte que alguien escucho mis gritos desesperados y saliÃ³ de su casa a observar, el tipo se asusta y saliÃ³ corriendoâ€¦

nunca pude hacer una denuncia porque no tenia pruebas y porque consideraba que no tenia sentido, dado que no iba a tener repercusiÃ³n alguna. solamente iba a ir a perder tiempo en la comisarÃ­a!

creo que es ya es hora que la justicia cambie completamente su forma de actuar y pensar. es tiempo haga lo que debe hacer que es actuar.

text: i'm celebrating my one year surgiversary y'all.  i am so happy and so proud!! i'm definitely not going back ever! i have several giveaways coming on my instagram @lezettechristinemua to celebrate.  i have had a few companies who donated to my success and i've also purchased some of my favorite products as well. i never thought i would be where i am today, alive and 140 pounds down. i had vsg 12/11/17 i was 348 pounds and dying because of my blood disease.  last year i was hospitalized every other week to receive a life saving infusion and now this year i only need to go in once every 2 months. its been nothing shy of incredible!! today i stepped on the scale and weighed in at 208. i also celebrated a nsv i was able to fit in a victoria secrets large top and a size 14 vigoss jeans not plus sized!! holy cow i'm on top of the world. i want to shout it from the rooftop seriously i'm so happy right now!! i am extremely strict, and dedicated i make sure to get in my protein,  water and vitamins. i walk a mile a few times a week and continue to fight. i would love to help you on your journey whether you are preop, post op or have fallen of the wagon. i'm here to tell you it's not too late every day is a new day and if you just have a little faith you can move mountains i post recipes,  motivation,  ideas and photos to help you all #bethebestversionofyou #againstallodds #aginginreverse #nevertoolate #youareenough #youcandoit #onestepatatime #bethechange #methemoglobinemia #metoo #knowyourworth #itstartswithone @lezettechristinemua

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words, every day.

the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and keep abusing the faith of their fellow men. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

a non

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words, every day.

the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and keep abusing the faith of their fellow men. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
it's been a long while, really long in fact. 12 years, i think but i'm not sure and it doesn't matter. 
we were in his room and he was chirpy, bubbly and all smiles because he had a date that evening. he was in class 11, i think and it was the first time that he was going out for a date. 
we were talking about her, i mean he was telling me about her and i was patiently listening. about her, her fam, how it started and about how exactly she looked. he described her like he was here for a police sketch session. i was confused, mildly bored and wanting him to stop. 
he went ahead and told me how he was planning to do unspeakable things to her that evening and the next moment 
the 
the next moment he had his mouth on mine and a terrified 8 odd year old was feeling something. i didn't know that it wasn't cool, i didn't think. i don't know much but all i know was this is not what i wanted. he stopped when he was done. later told me he was practicing his kiss before he could actually do one. he went ahead and i was there. made to feel like this was my purpose. made to feel like i'm obliged to give in. 
i have a bleak memory otherwise, it's strange how i remember so many details about him, that day, his room and that fuckall thing that he did.
i met that asshole of a person again today. i could not bang his face on to the wall so i thought i'll tell you. 
he doesn't make eye contact with me. wonder if he remembers. really wish he does. 
#metoo

text: 365 days ago i decided to do something that would change my life forever...i spoke up. this isnâ€™t something most people know about me, but iâ€™m apart of the metoo movement. it was one of the hardest things iâ€™ve ever had to do, go to my hr department and tell my story. amazingly this employee was terminated in 48 hours. my employer stood behind me every step of the way, but what i didnâ€™t realize was the retaliation i would receive from people that i worked with for years and were considered my friends. iâ€™ve had to rebuild myself over the past 365 days, itâ€™s been a difficult journey, but having the loving support of my family and close friends, reassuring me that what happened to me wasnâ€™t ok and needed to be reported. my message to the world is, know you're not alone and if something isnâ€™t ethically or morally right stand up and say something. i did what so many people couldnâ€™t do, and believe iâ€™ve saved some lives in the process. so blessed to have a new work family that brings out the sunshine and laughter in me! life happens...itâ€™s what you do with it that matters! â¤ï¸ #metoo #oneyearlater #rebuilding

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company â€œweaponisedâ€ the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how usersâ€™ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms â€“ facebook, in particular â€“ were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaignâ€™s lesser reported â€œweapons of mass destructionâ€. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someoneâ€™s personality. a userâ€™s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call â€œpopulist political signallingâ€. cambridge analytica, which wasÂ shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company â€œweaponisedâ€ the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how usersâ€™ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms â€“ facebook, in particular â€“ were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaignâ€™s lesser reported â€œweapons of mass destructionâ€. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someoneâ€™s personality. a userâ€™s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call â€œpopulist political signallingâ€. cambridge analytica, which wasÂ shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
there's a man back a-ways
who believes at where he is
and there's a girl
up ahead who says she knows

and the street overflows
with the folk who understand
but for the guy who can't be seen
he's the shadow man

and the shadow man is close at hand

take a turn and see his smile
made of nothing but loneliness
just take a walk and be a friend
to the shadow man

you can call him joe, you can call him sam
you should call and see who answers
for he promises to come running, guided by the truth

but the shadow man is really you

look in his eyes and see your reflection
look to the stars and see his eyes
he'll show you tomorrow, he'll show you the sorrows
of what you did today

you can call him foe, you can call him friend
you should call and see who answers
for he knows your eyes are drawn to the road ahead

and the shadow man is waiting round the bend
shadow man
waiting up the bend
shadow man
waiting up the bend
waiting up the bend

david bowie

text:
there's a man back a-ways
who believes at where he is
and there's a girl
up ahead who says she knows

and the street overflows
with the folk who understand
but for the guy who can't be seen
he's the shadow man

and the shadow man is close at hand

take a turn and see his smile
made of nothing but loneliness
just take a walk and be a friend
to the shadow man

you can call him joe, you can call him sam
you should call and see who answers
for he promises to come running, guided by the truth

but the shadow man is really you

look in his eyes and see your reflection
look to the stars and see his eyes
he'll show you tomorrow, he'll show you the sorrows
of what you did today

you can call him foe, you can call him friend
you should call and see who answers
for he knows your eyes are drawn to the road ahead

and the shadow man is waiting round the bend
shadow man
waiting up the bend
shadow man
waiting up the bend
waiting up the bend

david bowie
